{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_kendall_ver01/data/sn82014085/00393346851/1946032301/0297.xml":{"full_text":"Tall Tower\nTopics\nBY THE MAN IN THE TOWER\nGood Evening.\n_\u2666_\nMOSTLY FLORAL\n(N\u00abwt Item: Flower Shows Open Again First Time in Several Years)\nThe rose is going places\nVoted the Queen of Flowers,\nFashioned sweet in vases\nOr in cosy bowers.\nTulips and daffodils.\nOrchids rich and rare.\nClimbing stuff and shrubbery\nOn a horticultural tear.\nEverybody's at the show\nWhere it\u2019s flowers, flowers, flowers,\nGarden plants gone wild\nShowing off indoors!\n\u2014EM EM\n\\merican humor\u2014A Battalion Command Boat in\nJapan was visited by a constant stream of civiltaiiH seeR\ning information regarding occupation orders P\u00abbl,she\u201c\nby the American Army or seeking permission to start\nmanufacturing postwar products. Since many of them\ndid not speak English, an interpreter had to be kept in\nthe entrance merely to direct them to the proper other.\nSince the need for the interpreter in other places was\ngreater, it was decided to dispense with him by posting\ndirection and office signs in both English and Japanese.\nOne interpreter was assigned to the task of translating\nall American signs into Japanese characters. In an\nattempt to be as helpful as possible ho made an extra\nsign and posted it outside the door. Immediately, the\nJapanese civilians stopped coming into the building.\nWhen asked what his new sign said, he translated,\n\u201cThis building is the property of the American Armed\nForces. Anyone entering without permission will be\nshot on sight!\u201d\nThe Town Crier Tells. Some of the big towns sucn\nas Boston and New York are showing pretty posies this\nweek. Everything from orchids to stephanotis, and up in\nBoston a gal posed in an Avon (Conn.) \u201csurrey with the\nfringe on top. Cheshire calls attention to the fact that\nSpring has come and that the winter had done a good job\non nearby roads which are pretty well broken up by win\nter frosts. Oakville Boy Scouts\u2019 good deed for this week\nhappened during a recent hike when they freed an opos\nsum that was caught in a steel trap. Sullivan,\npopular druggist in Watertown has been in business *ijrty\nsevan years this week. Over near Horseshoe h alls,\nPequabuck, lots of rubbish is being dumped and Terry\nville selectmen are receiving plenty of complaints about\npassing motorists throwing tin cans and rubbish on private\nproperty along the highway. A shop that manufactures\nclothespins up in Hartland burned the other day, clothes\npins valued at $1,000 gone up in smoke.\nEditor of Tall Towers\u2014 Dear Sir: Your remarks\nregarding trees on the Green are of course interesting.\nToday more of the old elms are coming down. As an\nOld Timer, it reminds me of the small park in France on\nthe Champ Elysees, Place La Concorde, just across from\nHotel Criflon. The old trees there died and were re\nmoved. After study, the authorities planted what we\nknow as \u201cHorse Chestnut\u201d trees. Heavy foliage, beauti\nful white blossoms, nice shade. As to the small park\nitself, it is very attractive. It is not a kept Green, on\nthe contrary, the surface is nice, clean gravel. I he\nNuns march with squads of children for an airing and\nall play vary gracefully with rubber balls. Benches,\nyes, plenty, but you buy a ticket for a small copper coin\nfrom some very elderly woman and sit as long as you\nlike. Some real plans as to the future of \u201cOur Green\nare in order. Why not change its name and character,\nwhich are now outgrown and perhaps obsolete? Even\nstaid business men violate the \u201ckeep off the grass\nsigns. Better for children to use it than to risk their\nlives in traffic.\u2014XX, 11 Johnson Street, Waterbury.\nPacific Notebook (No. 6). Security regulations\nduring the war cloaked in secrecy the great pre-invasion\nwork done in the Pacific by under-water demolition\nteams. Volunteers, and skilled swimmers, it was their\njob to remove obstacles which the Japs had set up outside\nbeaches where they feared American landings. They car\nried out their assignments so well that they helped save\nthousands of lives and made important beachhead land\nings much safer (though safe is hardly ihe adjective for\nany beachhead) than they would have been otherwise.\nThe demolition teams, operating mainly at night, swam in\nsilently from offshore craft, to blow up mines, explode\nconcrete and barbed-wire barriers, and remove tracks set\nup by the enemy for amphibious tractors. Though the\nmembers of the teams rated no headlines back home, they\nhad the admiration and thanks of the assault troops w.ho\nhad the task of landing on hostile shores. After Marines\nhad succeeded in establishing a beachhead on Guam, a\nleathery old sergeant, burrowing deep into the sand for\nprotection from the hail of mortar and automatic weapon\nshells that covered the beach, commented: \u201cThis is no\npicnic, but we never would have got even this far, if those\nunderwater demolition boys hadn\u2019t cleared a path for us.\nTrees. There\u2019s no poem lovely as a tree, as the\npoet said, but once a tree gets sick and ailing, it is much\nbetter that it get the woodman\u2019s axe. There\u2019s no\n\u201cwoodman, spare that tree,\u201d when you find your elm is\ntoo far gone to save so that your children and grand\nchildren can sit under it as you did. That\u2019s why you\nwill see and are seeing so much chopping and cutting\nthis early Spring, about town and in adjacent towns.\nAlready they have started to do away with the elms-on\nthe-Green that are too far gone to save. This is the\ntree pruning time and everywhere you go trees are be\ning trimmed, some cut down, others deprived of a few\nbranches. The smell of dry wood on a warm March day\ntells the tale of lately cut wood. The fall of the elm\ntree is a sad event in New England. It took so long for\nthem to grow; but once their day is done, what a very\nshort time it takes to cut them down, one by one. This\nSpring, it is safe to say, more New England elms will\nbe cut off and down than in many years.\nFlowers in profusion, beautiful ami flagrant, were ob\nserved today by Mr. and Mrs. Alex 1. Forsell of 41 Arden\nRoad. They were expertly arrayed so that the eye of the\nexpert and the casual observer might share their unusual\nattractiveness. As Mr. and Mrs. Forsell mingled with\nhundreds of other lovers of flowers at the matchless New\nYork sxbibition, they were reminded of an event of ht)\nyears ago, by certain species of flowers that one usually\nassociate with weddings and bridal costumes. Today\nwas tho 39th anniversary of Mr. and Mrs. Korsell\u2019s wed\nding and a visit to the big flower show and to oilier at*'\ntractions In tha big city were just incidental to their cele\nbration. And today is also Mr. Korsell's birthday. Our\ncongratulations In abundance to the happy couple. Mr.\nForsell la a foreman in a Naugatuck factory, With Mrs.\nForsell, ha has one son and two grandchildren to mark\non tha highway called life. May they\nmore anniversaries fnd flower shows.\nGood Night.\nNew England Facing\nExcellent Prospects\nBlackall Claims Region\u2019s Business\nOutlook Brightest in Years:\nHigh Production Peaks Seen\nProvidence, R. I., March 33\u2014(UP)\n\u2014New England Is facing Us bright\nest business outlook In years, ac\ncording to President Frederick S,\nBlackall, Jr\u201e of the New England\nCouncil who said today that the re\ngion's industries should soon enjoy\nhigh production peaks.\nIn a speech prepared for the 82nd\nquarterly meeting of the council\nhere, Blackall said business pros\npects are excellent in textiles, leath\ner products, Jewelry, lumber and\nwood products and rubber.\nEven the New England farmer,\nhe said, has been producing at a\nfliigh level despite serious shortages\nof feed, fertilizer and farm machin\nery. Blackall added, however, that\nprice relief is essential if operating\nlosses and declining production are\nto be avoided. He said manufac\nturers in all the previously-men\ntioned industries are squeezed be\ntween low price ceilings and high\nlabor and material costs.\nA favorable factor for New Eng\nland industry was cited by Blackall\nas \"the growing trend toward decen\ntralization of the mass production\nindustries now centered in the\nmiddle west.\u201d\n\"It's efiects are evident in such\nnew developments us the establish\nment of tire General Motors plant\nat Framingham, Mass., and a re\nviving interest on the part of extra\nregional producers in subcontracting\nfor machined parts and other metal\nproducts among New England\nplants,\u201d he said.\nBlackall charged that reconver\nsion has not been as rapid as it\nshould have been, due to \"bureau\ncratic double talk which ignores the\ndirect relationship between labor\ncosts and prices, Ignores fundamen\ntals in economics and is largely re\nsponsible for the wave of strikes.\u201d\nNew England is facing \"a parting\nof the ways,\u201d he declared. One road\nleads to a rebirth of industrial\nmight while the other road leads to\ndecay and stagnation, he said.\n\"The recognition of basic econom\nic law and the natural incentives\nof freedom of enterprise are the\nthings which will make New Eng\nland greater if we adhere to them,\u201d\nBlackall said.\nThe Council was told by Rep. A.\nS. Mike Monroney, D\u201e Okla., that\nCongress must be reorganized if\nrepresentative government is to be\npreserved.\nHe said that Congress \"is trying\nto operate and supervise the world\u2019s\nlargest enterplse with an old-fash\nioned bookkeeper's stool, a slant top\ndesk, a Civil war ledger and a quill\npen.\u201d\nMonroney spoke in favor of the\npolicies of the LaFollette-Monroney\njoint committee on the organization\nof Congress. He said his committee\u2019s\n37-polnt program would rule out\nthe danger of government \"by one\nman.\"\nNo Progress\nIn Conference\nManagement and union conferees\nlulled again yesterday to settle their\ndifferences on local Issues in the\nstrike against the New Departure\nDivision of General Motors at Bris\ntol. The parties are expected to\nmeet against early next week.\nFifteen local issues remained un\nresolved when division officials and\na union committee adjourned their\nsession at 8:30 last night. They had\nbeen In conference since 10 a. m.\nSeven-Year\nOld Inquiry\nTerminated\nState Police Close\nCase After Long\nInvestigation\nBY SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT\nRockville, Conn., March 21\u2014A\nSlate Police case involving the\nabandonment of a baby here in\nMarch, 1939, was solved today, ex\nactly seven years from the day the\nabandonment was disclosed.\nParents of the baby, found in a\ntruck by Stanislaus Lemek of Elling\nton after he had parked the vehicle\non Main Street, have been located,\nand have given complete stories con\ncerning details of the abandonment.\nPolice indicated the parents of the\nbaby have been remarried, and since\nprovisions have been made for care\nof the child, now in a foster home,\nauthorities have agreed not to di\nvulge details of the situation to the\nnew marital partners of the man\nand woman.\nSolution of the case is credited to\nthe persistence of Chief Peter Dow\ngewicz, Lieut. William Barron of the\nManchester police, State Troopers\nSamuel S. Rome and Janes Finne\ngan, State Policewoman Evelyn J.\nBriggs and Lieut. Frank V. Chame\nroy, state police bureau of identifi\ncation director, who tracked down\nall of the details In* a painstaking\nhunt which had been complicated\nby repeated rumors.\nMIDDLEBURY\nCorresondent: Nancy Rileyi\n.Telephone 4-6410.\nMiddlebury, March 23\u2014Masses at\nSt. John of the Cross Church will\nbe celebrated tomorrow morning at\n7:30, 9 and 11 a. m.\nMrs. Agnes Proulx was hostess\nlast evening at her home to mem\nbers of the Women's Democratic\nClub.\nThe members of Ladies Auxiliary,\nVeterans of Foreign Wars will hold\na meeting on March 27. All ladies\neligible for membership are Invited\nto attend the meeting. Mrs. Eleanor\nHockert is acting as temporary\nchairman.\nRetail Stores\nFile Reports\nSales in Independent retail stores\nin Waterbury during January were\n3 per cent greater than in Janu\nless than those for December, 194*.\nThe U. S. Census Bureau reports\nthat the decline during January\nwas *2 per cent.\nThe average for Connecticut cities\nwas a gain of A2 per cent over\nJanuary, 1945, but a drop of the\nsame percentage from December.\nSales in Hartford were 14 per\ncent greater than a year ago, but\nwere down 44 per cent from Decem\nber. The situatlno was the same in\nBridgeport, New Haven and New\nBritain.\nWA VELETS\nBy BILL FARRINGTON\nBrig. Gen. Charles M. Spofford,\nnewly elected president of the Met\nropolitan Opera Association, will\nbe among the participants at the\n\"Opera Round Table\u201d during the\nMetropolitan Oporn broadcast\ntoday over WATR-ABC. The fea\nture will be held during the third\nIntermission of \"La Traviata\u201d at\n4:13 p. m\u201e EST. Other partici\npants will be Mrs. August Belmont,\nJulius Huehm and Florenza Quar\ntararo.\n\"Opera News on the Air,\u201d begin\nning at 2:38 p. m., EST. .again\nwill have Boris Goldovsky as mas\nter of ceremonies. Two young\nAmerican artists of the company\u2014\nDorothy Kirsten, soprano, and Rob\nert Merrill, baritone\u2014will be his\nguests.\nA newcomer to the \"Opera Quiz,\"\nat 3:32 p. m., EST, will be Virgil\nThompson, music critic of the\nHerald Tribune. Olin Downes\nagain will be quizmaster. Other ex\nperts will be Sigmund Spaeth and\nRobert Bagar.\n\"La Traviata,\u201d last but one of\nthis season\u2019s WJZ-ABC broadcast\nseries will begin at 2 p. m., EST.\nMilton Cross will be the announcer\ncommentator.\nAn Ironic twist of fate turns a\nholdup of great daring into a total\nfailure, even though the responsi\nble criminals are not quickly caught,\n;n the Gang Busters drama to be\npresented over WATR-ABC this\nevening at 9 p. m. A shipment of\ncurrency amounting to millions hi\ntransit to the Treasury De\npartment forms a tempting target\nfor any determined crook, and the\nspecimens represented in this broad\ncast of a true care history fail only\nbecause of an unforseeable acci\ndent and the immediate/ fast work\nof the police.\n\"The People vs Oscar Waller.\u201d the\nFamous Jury Trials drama to be\nheard tonight at 830 p, m. over\nWATR-ABC, tells a sordid tale of\ngangster double-, rossing. murder\nand perjury. Oscar Wuller, a\ngangster dealing in stolen goods,\nU tried for the mashiue-gunnliii;\nof a young mtaslK*'. killer when\nWuller was supposedly attempting\nto kill another gangster; but through\nthe perjury of his girl friend, he\nwas acquitted. Justice, in the\nform of the girl friend, whom lm\nspurned. deal* hint the punishment\nfrom which the jury saved him.\nPresident Harry I Truman and\nsecretary of Commerce Henry A.\nWallace will be heard In a special\nprogram to broadcast over Mutual\ntonight 14 to 10:M p m on the\nooceeton of the Jackson Day dinner\nto be held at the Mayflower Hot#!,\nWashington, D. 0.\nSecretary Wallace wlH open the\ngyreea ^nds gdijeewBcrtmjy\n\nFranco Autori, musical director\nand conductor of the Chautauqua\nSymphony Orchestra, will con\nduct the NBC Symphony Orches\ntra in two guest appearances,\nPalm Sunday. April 14, and Easter\nSunday, April 81, over NBC at 5\np. m. The programs will be short\nwaved to Italy.\nspeech of the President will be\nheard on the second half of the\nprogram.\nPap\u2019s Jug Band drops in for a visit\nat Roy Acuff\u2019s \u201cGrand Ole Opry\nIn the broadcast over WTXC tonight\nat 10:30 p. m. Pap and his Jug\ntooters will perform the comedy\nsong, \"You Two-Timed Me One\nTime Too Often.\u201d a new tune by\nJennie Lou Carson. Acuff sings\n\u201cNobody's Darling on Earth,\u201d a\ntouching heart song, and the hymn\n\u201cWhere Could I OoT\u201d The Old\nHickory Singers alio are slated for\ntwo tunes, Stephen Foster's \u201cBeau\ntiful Dreamer\" and the Gay Nineties\nhit, \u201cTwo Little CHrls In Blue.\" Re\nporting on the arrivsl of spring,\nWhitey Ford, the Duke of Paducah,\nsays, Today, I thought I saw the\nfirst robin redbreast oi Spring, but\nit turned out to be Just a fat spar\nl row wearing a red girdle.\" Tommy\nMagneas fiddles the modern \u201cOr\nange Blossom special.\" and Minnie\nPearl present* the latest bulletins\nfrom Qrmder s Switch Mack Me\nOsrr chooses Golden Slippers'' tor\nhis mandolin solo, and Acuffs\nSmoky Mountain Soys play \"Ar\nkansas Traveler\u201d as a Uvsly clossr.\nSATURDAY EVENING RADIO PROGRAMS\np. m. wm in* k-wj*\n6.00\u2014Varkee Network New*\n6:16\u2014Hit* and Bit*\n6:30 Hit* And Bit*\u2014New*\n6:4' \u2014Jim Britt\u2019* Roundup\n7:00\u2014It'* Tour Businees\n7:16\u2014Correspondents Abroad\n7:30\u2014Conn. Forum of the Air\n7:46\u2014Conn. Forum of the Air\n8:00\u2014Dick Tracy\n8:15\u2014Dick Tracy\n8:30\u2014Harry Savoy Show\n8:45\u2014Harry 8avoy Show\n9:00\u2014Gang Buster*\n9:15\u2014Gang- Busters\n9:3o\u2014 Boston Symphony\n9:45\u2014Boston Symphony\n10:00\u2014Boston Symphony\n10:15\u2014Boston Symphony\n10:30\u2014Hayloft Hoedown\n10:45\u2014Hayloft Hoedown\n11:00\u2014Yankee Network News\n11:15\u2014Ohes Paree Oroh.\n11:3d\u2014Clems For Thought\n11:48\u2014Stan Kenton Oroh.\n12:00\u2014Nows\u2014Sign Off\nWBltY IBM K-WABO\nQuincy How*\u2014New*\nAmerican Portrait\nAmerican Portrait\nWorld New#\nHelen Haye*\nHelen Hayes\nThe First Nlghter\nThe First Nlghter\nDick Haymes Show\nDick Haymes Show\nMayor of the Town\nMayor of the Town\u2014New*\nHit Parade\nHit Parade\nHit Parade\nJourney* in Jass\nJourney* In Jass\nContinental Club\nContinental Club\nTalks\nWorld and Docal Newe\nRrsklne Hawkln Orch.\nDancing in The Dark\nDancing In The Dark\nNews\u2014Sign Off\nWTIC 1600 K-WEAF\nNew*\nDon't Tou Believe It\nBob Stool*\nN. B. Forum of th* Air\nOur Foreign Policy\nOur Foreign Policy\nMoat Honored Flight*\nMoat Honored Fllghta\nLife Of Riley\nLife Of RUey\nTruth Or Conaequenc